    "\n",

   "source": [
    "## Background\n",
    "\n",
    "Grover's algorithm is an unstructured search algorithm that aims to find the input to a black-box function/oracle that returns a desired output value with high-probability.  Here we will show how to formulate such a search problem using Qiskit and it's circuit library to find Waldo within the following image:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "id": "607d2e02",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Plotting tools\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n",
    "from PIL import Image"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "id": "c640c3ca",
   "metadata": {
    "scrolled": false
   },

     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 960x720 with 16 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "fig, axes = plt.subplots(4, 4, figsize=[1.5*6.4, 1.5*4.8])\n",
    "for idx in range(16):\n",
    "    row_ind = idx // 4\n",
    "    current_axes = axes[row_ind, idx - 4*row_ind]\n",
    "    current_axes.imshow(Image.open('split/{}.jpg'.format(idx)))\n",

    "plt.subplots_adjust(wspace=0, hspace=0)"
   ]

    "The notion of \"where is Waldo\" needs to be made a bit more concrete before we can actually attempt such a search.  Here we will descretize the image into a 4x4 grid, and finding Waldo will come down to which of these 16 sub-images he is in.  Here the images are split in row-order as follows:"
   ]

    "plt.subplots_adjust(wspace=0.3, hspace=0.1)"
   ]
  },

    "## Setup\n",
    "\n",
    "The imports needed to run this notebook.  The plotting utilities are loaded above to display the images."
   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,

   "source": [
    "# Built-in modules\n",
    "import math\n",
    "\n",
    "# Imports from Qiskit\n",
    "from qiskit import QuantumCircuit\n",
    "from qiskit.circuit.library import GroverOperator, MCMT, ZGate\n",
    "from qiskit.visualization import plot_distribution\n",
    "\n",
    "# Imports from Qiskit Runtime\n",
    "from qiskit_ibm_runtime import QiskitRuntimeService, Sampler"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "63dc3b31",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Load Qiskit Runtime\n",
    "\n",
    "Here we load the runtime service, and select our target backends; one simulator for verification, and a real-device."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "id": "13e3c377",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "service = QiskitRuntimeService()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "id": "a5a090e5",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "sim = service.get_backend(\"ibmq_qasm_simulator\")\n",
    "backend = service.get_backend(\"ibm_cusco\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "ff5e1dea",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Oracle definition\n",
    "\n",
    "The oracle definition we use here is based on the `CZ` gate, which marks the all-ones bit-string with a negative phase value.  This is exactly what we want for a Grover oracle.  However, we are likely not interested in the all-ones bit-string, but rather some bit-string containing both ones and zeros.  We can modify the `CZ` gate, or its multi-controlled version, to mark states with zeros by using `X` gates on the qubits with a zero to yield an open-control on those qubits. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "id": "8464a89d",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def grover_oracle(marked_states):\n",
    "    \"\"\"Build a Grover oracle for multiple marked states\n",
    "\n",
    "    Here we assume all input marked states have the same number of bits\n",
    "\n",
    "    Parameters:\n",
    "        marked_states (str or list): Marked states of oracle\n",
    "\n",
    "    Returns:\n",
    "        QuantumCircuit: Quantum circuit representing Grover oracle\n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    if not isinstance(marked_states, list):\n",
    "        marked_states = [marked_states]\n",
    "    # Compute the number of qubits in circuit\n",
    "    num_qubits = len(marked_states[0])\n",
    "\n",
    "    qc = QuantumCircuit(num_qubits)\n",
    "    # Mark each target state in the input list\n",
    "    for target in marked_states:\n",
    "        # Flip target bit-string to match Qiskit bit-ordering\n",
    "        rev_target = target[::-1]\n",
    "        # Find the indices of all the '0' elements in bit-string\n",
    "        zero_inds = [\n",
    "            ind for ind in range(num_qubits) if rev_target.startswith(\"0\", ind)\n",
    "        ]\n",
    "        # Add a multi-controlled Z-gate with pre- and post-applied X-gates (open-controls)\n",
    "        # where the target bit-string has a '0' entry\n",
    "        qc.x(zero_inds)\n",
    "        qc.compose(MCMT(ZGate(), num_qubits - 1, 1), inplace=True)\n",
    "        qc.x(zero_inds)\n",
    "    return qc\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e54127b7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Setting marked state from images\n",
    "\n",
    "We require one or more \"marked\" states for Grover search.  Here I have marked the state with Waldo (a bit hastily) in it in the EXIF image data.  Below is a function that finds the marked state and returns the corresponding bit-string."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "id": "489ee47a",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "def get_marked_image():\n",
    "    \"\"\"Get the bit-string corresponding to the marked state with Waldo in it.\n",
    "    \n",
    "    Returns:\n",
    "        str: Bit-string for marked image \n",
    "    \"\"\"\n",
    "    marked_image = None\n",
    "    for idx in range(16):\n",
    "        img = Image.open('split/{}.jpg'.format(idx))\n",
    "        exif_data = img._getexif()\n",
    "        if exif_data:\n",
    "            if 34665 in exif_data:\n",
    "                marked_image = bin(idx)[2:].zfill(4)\n",
    "    if not marked_image:\n",
    "        raise Exception('Image not found')\n",
    "    return marked_image\n",
    "            "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "7eecb57d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Let us now use the above function to find the image with Waldo, and generate the corresponding Grover oracle:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 11,
   "id": "b0bda58d",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 371.107x367.889 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 11,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "marked_states = [get_marked_image()]\n",
    "oracle = grover_oracle(marked_states)\n",
    "oracle.draw(\"mpl\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "3c52d394",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Full Grover circuit\n",
    "\n",
    "To perform Grover iteration we need our oracle, and an operator that performs the amplification.  This is provided in the circuit library via the `GroverOperator`.  We can simply pass our oracle into this circuit building class:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 13,
   "id": "ee0144e3",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 927.658x367.889 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 13,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "grover_op = GroverOperator(oracle)\n",
    "grover_op.decompose(reps=1).draw(\"mpl\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f253d2cf",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We now have a single iteration of our Grover search, but that might not be enough.  Here we find the optimal number which is determined by the ratio of number of marked states to the total Hilbert space dimensionality:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 14,
   "id": "2c4b558e",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "optimal_num_iterations = math.floor(\n",
    "    math.pi / 4 * math.sqrt(2**grover_op.num_qubits / len(marked_states))\n",
    ")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "4208e06b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The final circuit becomes a state preparation of an equal superposition over all states using Hadamard gates, followed by repeated applications of our Grover iteration circuit the optimal number of times:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 15,
   "id": "a581dc68",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 914.831x451.5 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 15,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "qc = QuantumCircuit(grover_op.num_qubits)\n",
    "# Create even superposition of all basis states\n",
    "qc.h(range(grover_op.num_qubits))\n",
    "# Apply Grover operator the optimal number of times\n",
    "qc.compose(grover_op.power(optimal_num_iterations), inplace=True)\n",
    "# Measure all qubits\n",
    "qc.measure_all()\n",
    "qc.draw(\"mpl\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "117dcf87",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Verification on classical simulator\n",
    "\n",
    "Because our circuit is small, $\\lesssim 30$ qubits, we can easily validate it one a classical simulator.  Here we choose to sample our circuit using the cloud simulator:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 68,
   "id": "3fdb9729",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "sim_sampler = Sampler(sim)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 69,
   "id": "167cc8c8",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "sim_dist = sim_sampler.run(qc, shots=int(1e4)).result().quasi_dists[0]"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "40b40173",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "We plot the resulting distribution whose integer of maximal probability is (hopefully) the image where Waldo is located."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 70,
   "id": "12b00ca7",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {

      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 70,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "plot_distribution(sim_dist)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "0b5b7e37",

  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "925129c1",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Grover search is a problem very ill-suited for near-term hardware as the circuit depth grows quite rapidly with qubit count.  We could probably increase the granularity of the image to 5x6, which fits a 5-qubit circuit, but anything beyond that is likely to give poor results unless we put in a fair bit of effort to try to suppress errors."
   ]
